    "text": "
    Before the first cities, when the world was still wild and the people were few, the **Bone Singers** emerged from the caves of the **Black Maw**. They were not like other shamans—they did not dance or scream. Instead, they took the bones of the dead, carved them with strange marks, and sang to them in voices that were not their own. The bones *answered*. Not with words, but with truth.

    The first tribe to listen was the **Ashen Hand**, a people starving after a long winter. The Bone Singers told them: *‘The land is not yours to take. It is yours to keep.’* They taught the Ashen Hand to burn only what they needed, to bury their waste deep, to speak softly so the earth would not shake in anger. The tribe obeyed, and the land rewarded them—game returned to their traps, rivers ran clear, and their children did not sicken. Nearby tribes, watching, scoffed. *‘Superstition,’* they said. But when their own children coughed blood into the snow, they sent envoys to the Bone Singers.

    The Singers did not welcome them. *‘You come too late,’* they intoned. *‘The Hollow Pact is already broken.’* The envoys begged, and the Singers relented—but only if the outsiders would prove their faith. The ritual was simple: each must hold a burning bone until their flesh blistered, then press it to their chest, leaving a scar in the shape of the tribe’s mark. Those who flinched were turned away. Those who endured were given a single bone to carry, whispering secrets into it each night.

    The tribes who copied the ritual thrived. Their hunts were bountiful, their raids unstoppable. But the Bone Singers warned: *‘The pact is not forever. The land remembers.’* And so it did. When a tribe grew greedy, took too much, or turned on its own, the bones in their keeping would *crack*—not from age, but from anger. The scars on their chests would weep. The land would answer.

    Thus, the Bone Singers’ way spread—not because it was kind, but because it *worked*. And those who forgot? The earth swallowed them whole.
    "
