    For a time, the Thieves prospered. Their catches swelled. Their fires burned bright. But then the shore began to *shift*. The Thieves’ nets tore like paper. Their children were born with gills like dried seaweed, their voices stolen by the wind. Their homes, once sturdy, sank into the sand as if the ocean had pulled them under. The Wave-Speakers did not gloat. They only said, ‘The Current does not punish. It *remembers*.’

    The Drowned Ones did not celebrate. They knew the Rule was not cruel—only *true*. And so they lived, their steps steady, their trust unspoken but unbroken. The Salt Thieves? Their names faded into the foam, as if they had never walked the Blackshore.
